
[1]ministry

   MIN'ISTRY, n. [L. ministerium.] The office, duties or functions of a
   subordinate agent of any kind.

   1. Agency; service; aid; interposition; instrumentality.

   He directs the affairs of this world by the ordinary ministry of second
   causes.

   2. Ecclesiastical function; agency or service of a minister of the
   gospel or clergyman in the modern church, or of priests, apostles and
   evangelists in the ancient. Acts 1. Rom.12. 2 Tim.4. Num.4.

   3. Time of ministration; duration of the office of a minister, civil or
   ecclesiastical.

   The war with France was during the ministry of Pitt.

   4. Persons who compose the executive government or the council of a
   supreme magistrate; the body of ministers of state.

   5. Business; employment.

   He abhorred the wicked ministry of arms.
